<h2 id="but-we-werent-operating-in-the-same-reality">But we weren‚Äôt operating in the same reality</h2>

<p>That‚Äôs the part that changed how I think about this.</p>

<p>The issue wasn‚Äôt the output.</p>

<p>It was the gap between what the model assumed and what actually existed.</p>

<p>Paths. Files. Structure.</p>

<p>Nothing dramatic. Just‚Ä¶ slightly off.</p>

<h2 id="productive-is-what-it-looked-like-from-the-outside">Productive is what it looked like from the outside</h2>

<p>Alignment work is what it looked like from the inside.</p>

<p>And I do not think we have great language for that yet.</p>

<p>We talk about prompts.</p>

<p>We talk about outputs.</p>

<p>But the workflow‚Äîthe in-between‚Äîis mostly invisible.</p>

<p>Until you replay it.</p>

<h2 id="and-once-you-see-it-you-cant-unsee-it">And once you see it, you can‚Äôt unsee it</h2>

<p>I started noticing it everywhere.</p>

<p>The quick ‚Äúthat file‚Äôs not there.‚Äù<br />
The ‚Äúwrong folder.‚Äù<br />
The ‚Äúuse the other one.‚Äù</p>

<p>We don‚Äôt usually count those as part of the work.</p>

<p>But they are.</p>

<h2 id="so-i-changed-one-thing">So I changed one thing</h2>

<p>Not my prompts.</p>

<p>My approach.</p>

<ul>
  <li>I verify the environment earlier</li>
  <li>I slow down at the start</li>
  <li>I pay attention to corrections</li>
</ul>

<p>Because those corrections are not just interruptions.</p>

<p>They‚Äôre signals.</p>

<h2 id="we-might-be-optimizing-the-wrong-layer">We might be optimizing the wrong layer</h2>

<p>We‚Äôve been treating AI like a generation problem.</p>

<p>More and more, I think it is a systems problem.</p>

<p>Not: did the model produce the right output?</p>

<p>But: was the model operating in the right reality?</p>

<h2 id="try-this">Try this</h2>

<p>Record one session.</p>

<p>Replay it.</p>

<p>Not to critique it.</p>

<p>Just to see it.</p>

<h2 id="final-thought">Final thought</h2>

<p>I thought I needed better prompts.</p>

<p>What I actually needed was better visibility into the work I was already doing‚Äî</p>

<p>bringing the system back into alignment with reality.</p>

<p>I ran a Claude Code session for ten days.</p>

<p>Not ten days straight. Ten days of real work ‚Äî building, iterating, shipping posts, wiring up interactive components, updating docs. The kind of work I do every week now. When it was done, I exported the session data and went looking for something I couldn‚Äôt quite name.</p>

<p>I found it.</p>

<p>426 messages. 13.1 million tokens. And when I broke down what was actually happening in those messages ‚Äî not just ‚Äúuser sends prompt, assistant responds‚Äù but <em>what each message was doing</em> ‚Äî something uncomfortable came into focus.</p>

<p>Only about 37% of it was task work.</p>

<p>The rest? Alignment. Clarification. Confirmation. Iteration. Work that looked like prompting but was actually something else: the ongoing labor of getting two minds operating from the same reality.</p>

<p>Here‚Äôs the thing: none of that extra work was failure. The model wasn‚Äôt broken. I wasn‚Äôt prompting badly. Things got done. But the session data told a different story than ‚Äúproductive.‚Äù It told the story of how much invisible work hides inside every AI workflow ‚Äî and why we‚Äôve never had a name for it before.</p>

<h2 id="most-people-measure-the-wrong-thing">Most people measure the wrong thing</h2>

<p>When we talk about AI productivity, we measure outputs. Did the task complete? How fast? How many tokens did it cost?</p>

<p>These are real metrics. But they miss the layer underneath.</p>

<p>Think about what actually happens in a coding session with an AI. You describe a task. The model responds with something close to what you meant ‚Äî but not quite. You correct it. It adjusts. You verify the result, notice a filename doesn‚Äôt match, fix the reference, check the directory, confirm the output.</p>

<p>At every step, you are both <em>doing the task</em> and <em>negotiating shared context</em>. The task work and the alignment work happen simultaneously, and almost nobody tracks them separately.</p>

<p>I‚Äôve started calling the second kind <em>alignment tax</em>: the extra cycles spent not on the work itself, but on establishing the shared reality the work requires.</p>

<p>Alignment tax is not a bug. It‚Äôs not even avoidable. It‚Äôs a structural feature of how language models and humans collaborate. The model has no persistent memory of your project. It doesn‚Äôt know your file naming conventions, your aesthetic preferences, or that you named the file <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">context_window.svg</code> with an underscore. You know all of that. The model knows none of it until you tell it ‚Äî and you often don‚Äôt know you need to tell it until it guesses wrong.</p>

<p>What Tapes does is make this visible. Not to shame you for it. To help you see it clearly so you can work with it deliberately.</p>

<h2 id="let-me-show-you-what-i-mean">Let me show you what I mean</h2>

<p>Here‚Äôs a moment from my actual session. I asked the model to place images in a blog post. Simple task. The model created placeholder image paths ‚Äî reasonable defaults ‚Äî and completed the task.</p>

<p>Then I uploaded the real files.</p>

<p>The model had written <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ai-llms-models.svg</code>. The actual filename was <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ai-llms-model.svg</code>. One character difference. The model had written <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">context-window.svg</code>. The actual filename was <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">context_window.svg</code>. A dash versus an underscore.</p>

<p>The task was technically done twice: once with placeholder filenames, once with real ones. The second pass was alignment work ‚Äî reconciling what the model assumed against what actually existed on disk.</p>

<p>Neither pass was a failure. The session felt smooth in the moment. I didn‚Äôt notice the overhead.</p>

<p>But Tapes recorded it.</p>

<p>When I went back and looked at the session data, I could see the shape of it: <em>intent ‚Üí inspect ‚Üí adjust ‚Üí retry ‚Üí continue</em>. Not a straight line from task to output. A loop. And the loop wasn‚Äôt random. It had a structure. It always closed on the same gap: the gap between what the model assumed and what was true.</p>

<h2 id="three-kinds-of-alignment-work">Three kinds of alignment work</h2>

<p>After spending time in this session data, I started to see patterns. Alignment tax doesn‚Äôt show up as one thing. It shows up as three:</p>

<p><strong>Semantic alignment</strong> is when the model and you are using the same words to mean different things. In my session, the biggest instance of this was visual: I said ‚Äúsparkles‚Äù and meant blurry glowing halos like stars. The model implemented tiny 1‚Äì2px dots ‚Äî technically sparkles, but invisible at that size. The word ‚Äúsparkle‚Äù carried different visual assumptions on each side of the conversation. Three full iteration cycles happened before we landed on the same image.</p>

<p><strong>Structural alignment</strong> is when you and the model have different maps of the territory. I asked the model to find files in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">documents/ai blogpost</code>. The model didn‚Äôt have access to that directory. Neither of us knew that until the model tried. Structural alignment failures are easy to fix ‚Äî once you know the layout mismatch exists. The cost is the discovery.</p>

<p><strong>State alignment</strong> is the ongoing work of keeping the model current as reality changes. The blog post images I uploaded had different names than the placeholders. The database filename changed from <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tapes.db</code> to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tapes.sqlite</code>. Every time the ground truth shifted, there was alignment work to sync the model‚Äôs working assumptions. This isn‚Äôt a bug in the model. It‚Äôs a consequence of having no persistent memory.</p>

<p>Here‚Äôs what this looks like across a session:</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Intent ‚Üí Model assumes X ‚Üí Output based on X
         ‚Üë                          ‚Üì
         ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Correction: X is wrong, Y is true ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îò
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The loop always exists. The question is how long it runs and how visible it is.</p>

<h2 id="why-this-matters-more-than-you-think">Why this matters more than you think</h2>

<p>You might be reading this and thinking: ‚ÄúSure, there‚Äôs some back-and-forth. That‚Äôs just how prompting works.‚Äù</p>

<p>You‚Äôre not entirely wrong.</p>

<p>But here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve noticed: most developers I talk to underestimate how much of their ‚Äúprompting‚Äù is actually alignment work. They describe sessions as productive when they completed tasks. They don‚Äôt track the ratio of task work to alignment work. They don‚Äôt ask whether a specific category of task reliably generates more alignment overhead than others.</p>

<p>This is the data Tapes surfaces.</p>

<p>In my session, visual design tasks had the highest alignment tax by far. Describing what I wanted an interactive component to <em>look like</em> ‚Äî in words, to a model ‚Äî generated more correction cycles than any purely technical task. Renaming a file across a codebase: low alignment tax. Building CSS effects from a reference image: high alignment tax.</p>

<p>That‚Äôs useful to know. Not because it changes what I work on, but because it changes how I work on it. When I know a task category carries high alignment overhead, I can front-load the alignment work ‚Äî share the reference image first, establish the visual vocabulary explicitly, describe what I <em>don‚Äôt</em> want alongside what I do.</p>

<p>The developers who get the most out of AI tools aren‚Äôt necessarily the best prompters. They‚Äôre the ones who‚Äôve learned to recognize alignment work for what it is, and front-load it.</p>

<h2 id="what-tapes-actually-records">What Tapes actually records</h2>

<p>Tapes runs as a wrapper around Claude Code: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tapes start claude</code>. It captures the entire CLI session at the process level, writing to a local SQLite database in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">~/.tapes/</code>. Every message, every model response, every token count, every timestamp.</p>

<p>What this gives you:</p>

<ul>
  <li>A complete, searchable record of what happened in the session</li>
  <li>Token usage across the entire conversation, not just per-message</li>
  <li>The time dimension ‚Äî when did you come back to something? How long did an iteration loop run?</li>
  <li>The ability to replay and inspect specific moments</li>
</ul>

<p>That last one matters more than it sounds. Working in an AI session, you‚Äôre inside it. Things feel smooth or rough in real time. You don‚Äôt have the vantage point to see the shape of the whole thing. Tapes gives you that vantage point afterward.</p>

<p>I didn‚Äôt know I‚Äôd spent three full cycles trying to communicate ‚Äúsparkles that look like stars, not dust‚Äù until I looked at the session data. In the moment, it felt like iteration. In the data, it looked like a pattern ‚Äî and patterns are solvable.</p>

<h2 id="the-uncomfortable-truth-about-productive">The uncomfortable truth about ‚Äúproductive‚Äù</h2>

<p>We‚Äôve borrowed ‚Äúproductive‚Äù from a world where the work was legible. You wrote code, it compiled or it didn‚Äôt. You finished the feature, you didn‚Äôt. Productivity meant output per unit of time.</p>

<p>AI sessions scramble that. The work is less legible. Alignment work looks like task work from the outside ‚Äî you‚Äôre still sending messages, getting responses, moving forward. But the alignment work isn‚Äôt moving the task forward. It‚Äôs maintaining the conditions under which the task can move forward.</p>

<p>This is new. We don‚Äôt have great vocabulary for it yet. We don‚Äôt have metrics. Most AI productivity conversations are still about prompting quality, model capability, and output speed ‚Äî none of which touch the alignment layer.</p>

<p>Tapes is one of the first tools I‚Äôve seen that makes the alignment layer visible. Not through theory. Through data from your actual sessions.</p>

<p>What do you do with that visibility? That part is still being figured out. But you can‚Äôt work deliberately with something you can‚Äôt see. And most of us, right now, can‚Äôt see this.</p>

<p>That‚Äôs worth changing.</p>

